  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that the fastest path to valuable open‑source contributions—and the “open‑source millionaire” myth—is to turn problems you’ve already solved in your own projects into pull requests, rather than hunting “good first issue” tickets. It advises developers to scan their dependency files for libraries that caused pain, then document or fix the missing README, examples, metadata, or other documentation gaps that stemmed from those struggles. The tone is a high‑energy, informal tutorial peppered with emojis and slang, using the metaphor of “re‑basing away your desperate hacks” to frame personal pain points as reusable contributions. The piece targets active developers who regularly use third‑party libraries and want practical, low‑effort ways to build a contribution record and improve their communication skills.",
